    "summary": "The Golden Age of Tang Dynasty Poetry (c. 700–800 AD) represents the pinnacle of classical Chinese literature, producing a body of lyric verse that has defined Chinese aesthetic and cultural values for over a thousand years. The Tang period saw the apotheosis of Chinese poetry as an art form — the civil service examination required poetic composition, court culture celebrated verse, and the Tang capital Chang'an's sophisticated urban environment, combined with the empire's vast geographic reach and cultural diversity, provided poets with an unparalleled range of subjects, emotions, and experiences to transform into the precise, emotionally charged five- and seven-character regulated verses of the classical tradition.\n\nThe two poets who tower above all others — Du Fu (712–770) and Li Bai (701–762) — represent complementary poles of the Tang poetic tradition. Li Bai was celebrated in his own lifetime as the 'Immortal of Poetry': his verse is characterized by romantic exuberance, Taoist spirituality, celebration of wine and friendship, and imagery of startling originality and beauty. Du Fu, by contrast, was the 'Sage of Poetry': his work is marked by Confucian moral seriousness, deep compassion for human suffering (particularly the devastation of the [[event:2153|An Lushan Rebellion]], which he witnessed directly), and technical mastery of regulated verse forms. Other major Tang poets — Wang Wei (the 'Poet-Buddha,' famous for his landscape poetry and Buddhist sensibility), Bai Juyi (whose social critique poetry was deliberately written to be accessible), and many others — collectively produced an anthology of over 48,000 poems collected in the 'Complete Tang Poems,' which remains the authoritative canon of classical Chinese verse.",
